","1600":"1600","1564":"1564","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Donegal, County Cork, Ireland":"Donegal, County Cork, Irsko","Ballyshannon,Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Kildare, Irsko","Bailyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Irsko","Scotland":"Skotsko, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1515–1540":"1515–1540","1514–Male":"1514–Afdød","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1542–Male":"1542–Afdød","1485–1564":"1485–1564","1490–Female":"1490–Afdød","1514":"1514","1600":"1600","1564":"1564","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Donegal, County Cork, Ireland":"Donegal, County Cork, Irland","Ballyshannon,Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Kildare, Irland","Bailyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Irland","Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1515–1540":"1515–1540","1514–Male":"1514–Overleden","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1542–Male":"1542–Overleden","1485–1564":"1485–1564","1490–Female":"1490–Overleden","1514":"1514","1600":"1600","1564":"1564","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Donegal, County Cork, Ireland":"Donegal, County Cork, Ierland","Ballyshannon,Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Kildare, Ierland","Bailyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ierland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1515–1540":"1515–1540","1514–Male":"1514–Deceased","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1542–Male":"1542–Deceased","1485–1564":"1485–1564","1490–Female":"1490–Deceased","1514":"1514","1600":"1600","1564":"1564","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Donegal, County Cork, Ireland":"Donegal, County Cork, Ireland","Ballyshannon,Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Kildare, Ireland","Bailyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ireland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Donnell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Niall, Siobhan, Brennan, Bridie, Declan, Donal, Fergus, Jarlath, John Patrick, Padraic.","Irish (Donegal, Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Domhnaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Domhnall</i>’, an old personal name composed of the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. Compare the Anglicized form   Donald   and the Scottish clan name   McDonald  .","History: The O'Donnells, like the O'Neills (see   O'Neill  ), claim descent from Niall of the Nine Hostages (Niall Noígíallach), a legendary 5th-century king of Ireland. Their traditional base is Tyrconnell (i.e. Donegal)."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Donell","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Donnel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Daniel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  , influenced by the Biblical name   Daniel  , to which it is etymologically unrelated."]},{"name":"O'Donald","meanings":["Irish: Scotticized form of   O'Donnell  . The Irish personal name <i>Domhnall</i> was Latinized as <i>Donaldus</i>, which is the source of <i>Donald</i>, the form of the personal name used in English in Scotland, though not in Ireland. The form <i>O'Donald</i> is therefore a 19th-century hybrid. Compare   Donald  ."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan O'Donnell was born in 1515, in Ballyshannon, County Kildare, Ireland, her father, Mangus O'Donnell, was 30 and her mother, Joan O'Riley, was 25. She married Maurice MacGowan in 1530, in Donegal, County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1540, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1515–1540":"1515–1540","1514–Male":"1514–Surnud","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1542–Male":"1542–Surnud","1485–1564":"1485–1564","1490–Female":"1490–Surnud","1514":"1514","1600":"1600","1564":"1564","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1490":"1490","1